subSubSection.paragraph:
Diagnosis.
Species of the 

nivicola

-group; body black blue (
Fig. 1
); Ant IV dorsally with 6 sens (S1–2, S4, S7–9) and 5 ssc, 3 of which in “a”-set (a1–3), chaeta i absent; ventrally with 3 sa and 11 ssc (2 larger, 2 median and 7 short) (
Figs 3
A–B); four labral papillae (
Fig. 2C
); cephalic chaetotaxy with all chaetae subequal, except sd5, sd4, g1, g3, g5, g4`–5`gently largest; PAO with outer anterior lobe elongated, dorsal interocular tubercles not prominent (
Fig. 5
); labial palp with appendages d2 and e2 smaller, a1, b1 and b2 reduced and apically rounded, papilla E with small lp spine-like (
Fig 4A
); head to Abd V with 1, 1, 2, 1, 2, 2, 2, 2, 1 microgranular areas; Th II to Abd IV with additional chaetae (m2’, m3’, p3a, am) not frequent for the genus; Abd IV with p1–3 chaetae subequal in length; Abd V with p1 chaeta larger than p2 (
Figs 6A
, 
7
, 
8A
); Abd V–VI devoid of clavate chaetae, anal spine larger than basal tubercle (
Fig. 8
); tibiotarsus only with acuminate chaetae on proximal row (B1–6), M chaeta subequal to others (
Fig. 11
); collophore with 5 chaetae (
Fig. 13A
); manubrium dorsally with 12 chaetae (
Fig. 13B
); dens dorsally with 8–9 (4 larger) striated spines apically conical (commonly) and bi-, or tridentate in winter form (
Figs 13
C–D), summer form unknown; mucro boat-shaped with 1 dorsal subapical tooth (
Fig. 13D
).

Hypogastrura ottawana
sp. nov.
also resembles
H. tooliki in Ant
IV with 6 dorsal and 7 ventral sens (scc), four labral papillae, head with 2+2 vertical chaetae, Abd IV p1–3 chaetae with subequal length, Abd IV devoid of clavate chaetae, as well as clavate extra chaeta on tibiotarsus absent ( Tab. 1 ). However,
H. ottawana
sp. nov.
differs from this species by Ant I with 9 chaetae ( 8 in
H. tooliki
), head dorsal tubercle not prominent (clearly developed in
H. tooliki
), Abd IV with 1 (am) extra chaetae (absent in
H. tooliki
), Abd V with m1 and m3 chaetae (both absent in
H. tooliki
), anal sacs not everted (frequently everted in
H. tooliki
), and dens dorsally with 7–9 spines ( 2–3 in
H. tooliki
).
